  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Augustus Hesse is sorry to hear that Anne Warren Weston has been ill. He comments on the Civil War. He thinks Lee&apos;s army is making preparations for a new campaign against Washington and it would &quot;be surely demoralized and burned to ashes under the fire of the Fortifications around Washington&quot; if he tried to take that city.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">On the second page of the manuscript, Augustus Hesse continues the letter with the salutation, &quot;My dear friend.&quot; Hesse is troubled and apologizes because he thinks that his last letter may have offended Anne Warren Weston. Hesse wrote to Gov. John A. Andrew asking him for a furlough. Dr. Brown has promised an answer next week. Hesse&apos;s wound has healed, but he still has pain occasionally.</subfield>
  </datafield>
